Reasoning: The paper deals with the performance analysis of non-orthogonal multiple access (NOMA) in the uplink of a mobile network, which involves information theory (cs.IT), networking and internet architecture (cs.NI), systems and control (cs.SY), communications (cs.COMM), and machine learning (cs.LG) concepts. The paper discusses the impact of imperfect channel state information (CSI) and finite-length channel coding on the performance of NOMA, which are important topics in the above-mentioned sub-categories.
